      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(browser): preserve HTTP status in node-proxied browser errors",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- The node browser proxy (`runBrowserProxyCommand` in `extensions/browser/src/node-host/invoke-browser.ts`) collapsed a `>= 400` browser-route response into `new Error(<body.error>)`, **dropping the HTTP status**.\n- That error crosses the `node.invoke` boundary as a plain **string** (Error properties are not preserved over the RPC), so the gateway's stale-target retry classifier — `isChromeStaleTargetError` in `browser-tool.actions.ts`, which requires `msg.includes(\"404:\") && msg.includes(\"tab not found\")` — **never matches** a node-proxied `tab not found`. The existing drop-`targetId` retry never fires and the stale-`targetId` error surfaces to the agent.\n- This PR **preserves the status in the message** (`\"404: tab not found …\"`, `\"403: action targetId must match request targetId\"`) so the gateway's existing classification/retry works through the node proxy — restoring parity with the local browser path. It is a pure formatting change in the `>= 400` branch; validation and timeout error paths are untouched.\n\nOut of scope (follow-up): the `403 \"targetId must match request targetId\"` case is now correctly **classifiable** but still has no retry consumer. Adding a retry there is a separate request-normalization concern, intentionally not bundled here.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n### Behavior or issue addressed\nOn a gateway with a **remote browser node**, agents intermittently receive `tab not found` (404) or `action targetId must match request targetId` (403) from the browser tool when a cached `targetId` goes stale (tab closed / target rotated). The gateway already ships a drop-`targetId` retry for the stale-tab case, but it is gated on the surfaced error carrying the HTTP status token (`404:`). Because the node proxy strips the status, that retry never fires for **remote-node** browsers, and the error reaches the agent.\n\n### Real environment tested\n- **Before fix** — observed live on an OpenClaw gateway **v2026.5.27** with a remote macOS Chrome node reached via `browser.proxy` (the relevant code on `main` is unchanged from v5.27).\n- **After fix** — the `@openclaw/browser-plugin` package test suite, which exercises the real `runBrowserProxyCommand` code path.\n\n### Exact commands run after this patch\n```\nnode scripts/test-projects.mjs extensions/browser/src/node-host/invoke-browser.test.ts\n```\n\n### Evidence — before fix (live gateway log, remote node; conn/id redacted)\n```\n⇄ res ✗ node.invoke 116ms errorCode=UNAVAILABLE errorMessage=INVALID_REQUEST: Error: action targetId must match request targetId conn=… id=…\n⇄ res ✗ node.invoke 115ms errorCode=UNAVAILABLE errorMessage=INVALID_REQUEST: Error: action targetId must match request targetId conn=… id=…\n# and the 404 variant from the same class:\n⇄ res ✗ node.invoke … errorMessage=INVALID_REQUEST: Error: tab not found: browser tab \"…\"\n```\nThe surfaced messages carry **no `<status>:` token**, so `isChromeStaleTargetError` returns `false` and no retry is attempted.\n\n### Evidence — after fix (test output)\n```\n RUN  v4.1.7\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  14 passed (14)\n```\nNew / updated assertions in `invoke-browser.test.ts`:\n- a `500` proxy error now surfaces as **`\"500: tab not found\"`** (status preserved), and\n- a `404 {error: \"tab not found: …\"}` now surfaces as **`\"404: tab not found …\"`** — i.e. it now carries both `404:` and `tab not found`, the exact tokens `isChromeStaleTargetError` requires, so the existing drop-`targetId` retry will fire.\n\n### Observed result after fix\nNode-proxied browser errors retain their HTTP status, restoring the gateway's stale-target classification/retry for **remote** browser nodes (parity with the local browser path).\n\n### Evidence — after fix (live run of the shipped gateway classifier)\n\nBeyond the package tests above, I ran the **actual shipped gateway classifier** against the before/after node-proxied error strings on a live gateway. `isChromeStaleTargetError` was extracted **verbatim** (brace-matched) from the installed production build's `plugin-service-*.js` and `eval`'d, then fed the `>= 400` proxy output as formatted by the **shipped** logic (status dropped) vs **this patch** (status preserved):\n\n```\n404 tab-not-found (stale targetId):\n  BEFORE (shipped):  Error(\"tab not found: …\")        isChromeStaleTargetError(\"user\", …) -> false   (retry NOT fired — the bug)\n  AFTER  (patched):  Error(\"404: tab not found: …\")    isChromeStaleTargetError(\"user\", …) -> true    (drop-targetId retry now FIRES)\n\n403 targetId-mismatch:\n  BEFORE (shipped):  Error(\"action targetId must match request targetId\")          -> false\n  AFTER  (patched):  Error(\"403: action targetId must match request targetId\")      -> false   (status now preserved/classifiable; 404-retry intentionally not consumed — see Out of scope)\n\nRESULT: PASS — fix restores the gateway stale-target retry for node-proxied 404s; 403 unchanged.\nnode v22.22.0 | classifier sourced verbatim from /usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw (v2026.5.27)\n```\n\nThe shipped classifier body that gated this (verbatim from the installed build):\n\n```js\nfunction isChromeStaleTargetError(profile, err) {\n  if (!profile) return false;\n  if (profile === \"user\") {\n    const msg = String(err);\n    return msg.includes(\"404:\") && msg.includes(\"tab not found\");\n  }\n  // …non-\"user\" profiles resolve browser config; the default path returns on the gate above\n}\n```\n\nThis exercises the decisive half end-to-end with real shipped code: the gateway's retry classifier was returning `false` for node-proxied `tab not found` (status stripped), and returns `true` once this patch preserves the status — so the existing drop-`targetId` retry now fires for remote-node browsers.\n\n### What was not tested in this PR\nThe patched `runBrowserProxyCommand` was not executed inside a full browser-node process against real Chrome with the production gateway↔node RPC hop. The patched **producer** output is covered by the package vitest (the real `runBrowserProxyCommand` code path); the **consumer** (the shipped gateway `isChromeStaleTargetError`) is run live above against the real before/after strings. A full gateway + remote-node live-browser capture can follow on request.\n",
